is it possible to have five spleens no you should only have one spleen within the spleen there are three areas of the organ that are recognized the head body and tail of the spleen this is to facilitate the location of any lesion or abnormalities by physicians very very rarely there are some patients with accessory spleens but these organs are much smaller than the actual true spleen and they are called accessory spleens because histologically they have the same cellular architecture as a normal spleen through further diagnostic testing these accessory organs may also behave in a similar manner as a true spleen but usually much less functional from a physiological standpoint hope this helps and answers your question Spleen Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Sickle-cell disease Platelet Multiple sclerosis Cancer Lymphatic system Atherosclerosis Stomach cancer Cephalic disorder Anemia Autism Aphasia Hypoglycemia Cerebellum Growth hormone treatment Anatomy Tooth enamel Chronic fatigue syndrome Prostate cancer Acupuncture Malignant melanoma Metastasis Pneumonia Inborn error of metabolism Syphilis Brain tumor Diagnosis Atrial septal defect Endocrinology History of brain imaging Androgen insensitivity syndrome Infectious mononucleosis Gaucher's disease Endoscopy Hunter syndrome Mesothelioma Biology Lupus erythematosus Diabetes mellitus Acute lymphoblastic leukemia Cytomegalovirus Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura Organ transplant History of anatomy in the 17th and 18th centuries Physician Histology Turner syndrome Hereditary spherocytosis Ovarian cancer Balance disorder Post-traumatic stress disorder Leukemia Iron deficiency anemia Normal distribution Hypnosis Atheroma Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease Uterine fibroids Fibromyalgia Cervical cancer Narcolepsy Traditional Chinese medicine AIDS reappraisal Chronic lymphocytic leukemia Angina Coronary catheterization Endometrial cancer Ernest McCulloch Esophagogastroduodenoscopy Cirrhosis Osteopathy Red blood cell Radiosurgery Kaposi's sarcoma